# Radial Head

> The **radial head** is the disk-shaped proximal end of the [[Radius]], articulating with the **capitulum** of the [[Humerus]] (radiocapitellar joint) and the **radial notch** of the [[Ulna]] (proximal radioulnar joint — PRUJ), allowing forearm rotation.

## 🔗 Key Connections
- [[Radius]] — proximal end
- [[Humerus]] — articulates with capitulum (radiocapitellar joint)
- [[Ulna]] — articulates with radial notch (proximal radioulnar joint)
- Annular ligament — encircles the radial head; holds it against the ulna

## 🏥 Clinical Significance
- **Radial head fracture** — Most common elbow fracture in adults; fall on outstretched hand
- **Mason classification** — I (non-displaced), II (partial, displaced), III (comminuted), IV (+elbow dislocation)
- **Nursemaid's elbow (annular ligament displacement)** — In children <5: subluxation of radial head from annular ligament; arm held pronated after traction injury
- **Posterior interosseous nerve** — Deep radial nerve wraps around the radial neck just distal to the head; at risk in fractures

